{"parse":{"title":"Afterword","pageid":1419427,"revid":738739345,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">\"Afterwords\" redirects here. For other uses, see <a href=\"/wiki/Afterword_(disambiguation)\" class=\"mw-disambig\" title=\"Afterword (disambiguation)\">Afterword (disambiguation)</a>.</div>\n<div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">Not to be confused with <a href=\"/wiki/Afterward\" title=\"Afterward\">Afterward</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/After_Words\" title=\"After Words\">After Words</a>.</div>\n<p>An <b>afterword</b> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Literary_device\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Literary device\">literary device</a> that is often found at the end of a piece of <a href=\"/wiki/Literature\" title=\"Literature\">literature</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It generally covers the story of how the book came into being, or of how the idea for the book was developed. \n</p><p>An afterword may be written by someone other than the <a href=\"/wiki/Author\" title=\"Author\">author</a> of the book to provide enriching comment, such as discussing the work's historical or cultural context (especially if the work is being reissued many years after its original publication).<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Afterword&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Conclusion_(book)\" title=\"Conclusion (book)\">Conclusion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Epilogue\" title=\"Epilogue\">Epilogue</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Foreword\" title=\"Foreword\">Foreword</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Postface\" title=\"Postface\">Postface</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Postscript\" title=\"Postscript\">Postscript</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Afterword&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/afterword\">\"afterword\"</a>. Dictionary.com, LLC. Retrieved 10 August 2012. </span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Pope, Geoff (18 November 2010). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://grammar.quickanddirtytips.com/forward-versus-foreword.aspx\">\"<span style=\"padding-left:0.2em;\">\"</span>Foreword\" Versus \"Forward<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">\"</span>\"</a>. <i>Grammar Girl's Quick and Dirty Tips</i>. MacMillan Holdings, LLC<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">10 August</span> 2012</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Grammar+Girl%27s+Quick+and+Dirty+Tips&amp;rft.atitle=%22Foreword%22+Versus+%22Forward%22&amp;rft.date=2010-11-18&amp;rft.aulast=Pope&amp;rft.aufirst=Geoff&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fgrammar.quickanddirtytips.com%2Fforward-versus-foreword.aspx&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAfterword\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</l